node.text:
The footage captured earlier by Rich Horner showed him swimming in Manta Point, a famous diving site about 20km from the popular tourist island. 🏊‍♂️ It's no secret that Bali has a problem with rubbish, but even Mr. Horner, a Bali resident, said he had "never seen anything on this scale" before. 😬 Where is it all coming from? 🤔 Bali sits in the middle of the Indonesian Throughflow, a current that streams from the Pacific Ocean into the Indian Ocean through the straits of Indonesia. 🇮🇩 This means that plastic waste could either be local or brought in from as far away as the Pacific Ocean. 🌊 “The plastic I saw mainly had Indonesian labelling but because of the current could be coming from anywhere in Indonesia, the Philippines, Malaysia [or] beyond," said Mr Horner. "There's a lot of cleaning initiatives around Bali and regular beach clean-ups, but the thing is that a lot of the rubbish is coming here from Java [Indonesia's main island]." Via @recycleseas 🙏

node.text:
Beautiful moments and sentiments with @oceanramsey & @juansharks - "When 'all the sharks align' and you know you’re in the right place at the right time and years and years of work and experience all come together for an opportunity to experience the very best life can offer. Magical moments in the deep blue with 'Grandma Great White' My great-grandmother used to swim off the south shore of Oahu everyday till she died, 'Grandma great white' featured here is actually larger than 'Deep Blue' who was around the day before this footage. I’ve been swimming with sharks my whole life and working professionally with them for almost 20 yrs. There’s a challenge I have in my efforts to find a balance between helping people to overcome their fear of sharks that often stems from fictitious media, and instilling a healthy level of respect for sharks. I reached the decision, long ago, to devote the rest of my life to conservation, research, and education. I hope my efforts inspire action for conservation and compassion for heavily misunderstood apex predators and other important marine life. I also hope that it means that more beautiful sharks like this will be saved from wasteful finning for sharks fin soup, shark fishing, or other wasteful things like shark nets, bycatch from industrial longline fleets, or even the pharmaceutical and souvenir trade. Learn more and get involved in helping to save sharks by sharing the letter from HelpSaveSharks.Org with any store, restaurant, or company the sells or ships shark derived products."

🎥 @juansharks, edited by @jarebutter
📝 by @oceanramsey
📍 Oahu, Hawaii

node.text:
For five years after the BP #DeepwaterHorizon disaster, more than 75% of all dolphin pregnancies in the oiled area failed.
.
Today marks 10 years since this disaster, the worst oil spill in U.S. history. In addition to the long-term negative effects on dolphins, more than 150 dolphins and whales were found dead following the spill.
.
📸: Julie Dermanksy

node.text:
Sea Turtles have been swimming in our oceans for many years, since dinosaurs roamed the earth 🌎 
These ancient beings travel thousands of kilometers of open ocean, migrating between foraging grounds and nesting grounds. Amazingly, all female sea turtles return to nest on the same beaches they hatched on!
In order to keep turtles around for many more years to come we have to remember to respect their home! 
#TurtleTrend
VC @sealegacy

The Australian Giant Cuttlefish (Sepia apama) is the largest of all cuttlefish species in the world and an expert at color change and camouflage. Over its three-year lifespan, it can grow up to 5ft in length and weigh over 23lbs. 👾 
Video by @aleksmutated
